<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>When the Federal Reserve conducts open market operations, what do they trade?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Corporate stocks</option>
            <option letter="b">Government securities</option>
            <option letter="c">Foreign currency</option>
            <option letter="d">Commodities</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The Fed primarily conducts open market operations by buying and selling U.S. government securities in the secondary market.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>How does the money multiplier change when banks hold excess reserves?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">It increases</option>
            <option letter="b">It decreases</option>
            <option letter="c">It stays the same</option>
            <option letter="d">It becomes negative</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When banks hold excess reserves, the money multiplier decreases because less money is being lent out and re-deposited in the banking system.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>Under the Bretton Woods system, how did countries maintain fixed exchange rates?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">By trading exclusively in gold</option>
            <option letter="b">By intervening in currency markets</option>
            <option letter="c">By prohibiting international trade</option>
            <option letter="d">By printing unlimited money</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Countries maintained fixed exchange rates by buying or selling their currencies in foreign exchange markets, using dollar reserves to maintain the agreed rates.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>What was the primary function of money that commodity money performed better than early paper money?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Medium of exchange</option>
            <option letter="b">Store of value</option>
            <option letter="c">Unit of account</option>
            <option letter="d">Standard of deferred payment</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Commodity money (like gold) performed better as a store of value because it had intrinsic worth and couldn't be debased like paper money could.</explanation>
    </question>

    <question>
        <prompt>In bank T-accounts, what happens when a bank sells securities to the Fed?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Assets and liabilities both increase</option>
            <option letter="b">Assets stay same, composition changes</option>
            <option letter="c">Only liabilities increase</option>
            <option letter="d">Only assets increase</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>When a bank sells securities to the Fed, its total assets stay the same but the composition changes: securities decrease and reserves increase by the same amount.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
